<br>
Due to the difficulty of collecting and processing 100 odd tones of water remotely, and the uncertainty of being able to collect it at all, you might have to dril for it but there are no gaurantees, nor is there any gaurantee that water ice can be found on the surface near enough to the landing site to exploit, Zubrin chose to utilize a technique that has a 100% chance of working.<br>
<br>
The process is as follows. <br>
<br>
1)6.5tonnes of hydrogen feedstock are brought from earth with the ERV(earth return vehicle)<br>
<br>
2)CO2 is combined with hydrogen in a reaction know as the Sabatier process(which has been used by industry here on earth for over a century) to produce CH4(methane, aka natural gas)  and H2O.<br>
<br>
3)Electrolysis is used to split the H2O into hydrogen and oxygen.  The Oxygen is liqufied and stored for use as breathing air or propellent, the hydrogen goes back into the Sabatier reaction.<br>
<br>
4)The combination of the Sabatier process and electrolysis can produce plenty of methane, but not enough oxidiser for the trip home.  Therefore, a third reaction called the &quot;Reverse Water Gas Shift&quot;, RWGS, is used.  Some of the hydrogen from the electrolysis is diverted from the Sabatier reaction to another reaction chamber where it is combined with CO2 to produce CO and H2O.  The carbon monoxide is vented, the water is electrolysised to produce more hydrogen, which can either be used again by the Sabatier or RWGS reactions and more oxygen, which is stored.<br>
<br>
These reactions together can turn 6.5 tons of hydrogen and unlimited martian CO2 into 108 tons of methane/oxygen bipropellent.  This is an increase by a factor of almost 17.  In addition, all the chemistry involved is simple and has been know to industrial chemists for centuries.  The Sabatier process is exothermic(produces heat) while the RWGS is endothermic(requires heat),these two compliment nicely, and if run side by side and with the proper catylists, would require very little energy input.  Most of the 100kWe required is for the electrolysis.  Plus the resource utilized, the martian atmosphere, is present in know, and garanteed, amounts at every possible landing site. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1033<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 12:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=811.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Zubrins route to Mars by chemical rocket, and its vairie</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/1690768.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
